00:01:12.302 --> 00:01:14.010
We started off with
just three equations.

00:01:14.010 --> 00:01:16.710
We conserve mass,
energy, and momentum.

00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:19.320
Mass and energy-- let's see--

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:21.270
come from the same equation.

00:01:21.270 --> 00:01:28.320
c squared plus T1 plus
M2 c squared plus T2

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:37.260
has to equal M3 c squared plus
T3 plus M4 c squared plus T4.

00:01:37.260 --> 00:01:40.230
We started off making
one quick assumption,

00:01:40.230 --> 00:01:43.260
that the nucleus 2, whatever
we're firing things at,

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:44.670
has no kinetic energy.

00:01:44.670 --> 00:01:47.115
So we can just forget that.

00:01:47.115 --> 00:01:48.810
What we also said
is that we have

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:51.660
to conserve x and y momentum.

00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:54.600
So if we say the x
momentum of particle 1

00:01:54.600 --> 00:02:00.930
would be root 2 M1 T1
plus 0 for particle 2,

00:02:00.930 --> 00:02:04.650
because if particle 2 is not
moving, it has no momentum.

00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:12.090
Has to equal root 2
M3 T3 cosine theta,

00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:15.480
because it's the x
component of the momentum,

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:21.740
plus root 2 M4 T4 cosine phi.

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:23.880
And the last equation
for y momentum--

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:29.940
we'll call this x momentum,
call that mass and energy,

00:02:29.940 --> 00:02:33.360
call this y momentum--

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:37.050
was-- let's say there's no
y momentum at the beginning

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:38.350
of this equation.

00:02:38.350 --> 00:02:41.550
So I'll just say 0 plus 0.

00:02:41.550 --> 00:02:45.450
Equals the y component of
particle 3's momentum, root

00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:52.230
2 M3 T3 sine theta, minus--

00:02:52.230 --> 00:02:53.730
almost did that
wrong-- because it's

00:02:53.730 --> 00:03:02.800
going in the opposite direction,
root 2 M4 T4 sine phi.

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:09.140
We did something, and we
arrived at the Q equation.

00:03:09.140 --> 00:03:11.805
I'm trying to make sure we
get to something new today.

00:03:11.805 --> 00:03:13.430
So the Q equation
went something like--

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:16.110
and I want to make sure that
I don't miswrite it at all.

00:03:23.650 --> 00:03:25.320
So when we refer
to the Q equation,

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:29.700
we're referring to this highly
generalized equation relating

00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:31.342
all of the quantities
that we see here.

00:03:31.342 --> 00:03:33.300
So I'm not going to go
through all of the steps

00:03:33.300 --> 00:03:34.758
from last time,
because, again, you

00:03:34.758 --> 00:03:36.810
have a picture of the
board from last time.

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:47.550
But it went Q equals T1 times M1
over M4 minus 1 plus T3 times 1

00:03:47.550 --> 00:04:01.348
plus M3 over M4 minus 2 root
M1 M3 T1 T3 cosine theta.

00:04:01.348 --> 00:04:03.640
And last time we talked about
which of these quantities

00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:05.230
are we likely to
know ahead of time

00:04:05.230 --> 00:04:07.480
and which ones might
we want to find out.

00:04:07.480 --> 00:04:09.460
Chances are we know all
of the masses involved

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:13.210
in these particles,
because, well, you guys have

00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:15.790
been calculating that for the
last 2 and 1/2 weeks or so.

00:04:15.790 --> 00:04:17.920
So those would be
known quantities.

00:04:17.920 --> 00:04:22.360
We'd also know the Q value for
the reaction from conservation

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:24.160
of mass and energy up there.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:27.310
And we'd probably be controlling
the energy of particle 1

00:04:27.310 --> 00:04:28.060
as it comes in.

00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:29.920
Either we know--
if it's a neutron,

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:31.397
we know what energy
it's born at.

00:04:31.397 --> 00:04:32.980
Or if it's coming
from an accelerator,

00:04:32.980 --> 00:04:36.040
we crank up the voltage on the
accelerator and control that.

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:39.010
And that leaves us
with just three quant--

00:04:39.010 --> 00:04:41.080
two quantities that
we don't know--

00:04:41.080 --> 00:04:44.800
the kinetic energy of
particle 3 and the angle

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:47.030
that it comes off at.

00:04:47.030 --> 00:04:50.580
So this was the highly,
highly generalized form.

00:04:50.580 --> 00:04:55.220
Recognize also that this is a
quadratic equation in root 3,

00:04:55.220 --> 00:04:56.135
or root T3.

00:05:01.940 --> 00:05:09.180
And we did something
else, and we

00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:16.140
arrived at root T3 equals
s plus or minus root s

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:21.700
squared plus t, where s and t--

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:22.200
let's see.

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:33.980
I believe s is root M1 M3 T1
cosine theta over M3 plus M4.

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:36.510
And we'll make a
little bit more room.

00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:40.270
t should be-- damn
it, got to look.

00:05:40.270 --> 00:05:40.770
Let's see.

00:05:40.770 --> 00:05:46.232
I believe it's minus M4 Q plus--

00:05:46.232 --> 00:05:50.078
oh, I'll just take a quick look.

00:05:50.078 --> 00:05:51.620
All right, I have
it open right here.

00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:54.141
I don't want to give you a
wrong minus sign or something.

00:05:56.860 --> 00:05:58.110
I did have a wrong minus sign.

00:05:58.110 --> 00:05:58.950
Good thing I looked.

00:06:04.175 --> 00:06:12.160
1 times E1 over M3 M4.

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:13.870
And so we started
looking at, well,

00:06:13.870 --> 00:06:16.960
what are the implications
of this solution right here?

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:25.350
For exothermic reactions,
where Q is greater than 0,

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:28.710
any energy E1 gets
this reaction to occur.

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:32.220
And all that that says, well,
it doesn't really say much.

00:06:32.220 --> 00:06:34.195
All that it really
says is that E3--

00:06:34.195 --> 00:06:40.140
I'm sorry-- T3-- and let me
make sure that I don't use any

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:42.420
sneaky E's in there--

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:46.770
plus T4 has to be greater
than the incoming energy T1.

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:48.840
That's the only real
implication here,

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:51.780
is that some of the mass
from particles 1 and 2

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:55.940
turned into some kinetic
energy in particles 3 and 4.

00:06:55.940 --> 00:06:59.480
So that one's kind
of the simpler case.

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:06.120
For the endothermic case,
where Q is less than 0,

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:09.350
there's going to be some
threshold energy required

00:07:09.350 --> 00:07:14.210
to overcome in order to
get this reaction to occur.

00:07:14.210 --> 00:07:17.300
So where did we say?

00:07:17.300 --> 00:07:19.550
So, first of all, where
would we go about deciding

00:07:19.550 --> 00:07:22.575
what is the most favorable
set of conditions

00:07:22.575 --> 00:07:24.200
that would allow one
of these reactions

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:27.448
to occur by manipulating
parameters in s and t?

00:07:27.448 --> 00:07:29.490
What's the first one that
you'd start to look at?

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:37.960
Well, let's start by
picking the angle.

00:07:37.960 --> 00:07:39.610
Let's say if there
was a-- if we had

00:07:39.610 --> 00:07:41.590
what's called
forward scattering,

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:45.730
then this cosine
of theta equals 1.

00:07:45.730 --> 00:07:48.850
And that probably gives
us the highest likelihood

00:07:48.850 --> 00:07:52.002
of a reaction happening, or
the most energy gone into,

00:07:52.002 --> 00:07:53.710
let's say, just moving
the center of mass

00:07:53.710 --> 00:07:57.025
and not the particles going
off in different directions.

00:07:57.025 --> 00:07:57.525
Let's see.

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:05.010
Ah, so what it really
comes down to is

00:08:05.010 --> 00:08:08.670
a balance in making sure
that this term right here,

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:11.020
well, it can't go negative.

00:08:11.020 --> 00:08:13.440
If it goes negative, then
the solution is imaginary

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:15.630
and you don't have
anything going on.

00:08:15.630 --> 00:08:17.430
So what this implies
is that s squared

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:23.070
plus t has to be greater or
equal than 0 in order for this

00:08:23.070 --> 00:08:25.320
to occur.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:27.500
Otherwise, you would
have, like I said,

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.847
a complex solution to an energy.

00:08:29.847 --> 00:08:31.430
And energy is not
going to be complex.

00:08:31.430 --> 00:08:34.570
That means the
reaction won't occur.

00:08:34.570 --> 00:08:36.760
So this is where we
got to last time.

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:37.260
Yes.

00:08:37.260 --> 00:08:40.890
AUDIENCE: When you say s
squared plus t is greater than 0

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:43.169
or greater than or equal
to 0, it's endothermic,

00:08:43.169 --> 00:08:45.390
wouldn't it also be
greater than or equal to 0

00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:46.290
for an exothermic?

00:08:46.290 --> 00:08:47.290
MICHAEL SHORT: It would.

00:08:47.290 --> 00:08:48.870
But there's a
condition here that--

00:08:48.870 --> 00:08:49.860
lets see.

00:08:49.860 --> 00:08:52.710
In this case, for
exothermic, Q is greater

00:08:52.710 --> 00:08:55.230
than 0 and that condition
is always satisfied.

00:08:55.230 --> 00:08:58.030
For an endothermic
reaction, Q is negative.

00:08:58.030 --> 00:09:00.310
So that's a good point.

00:09:00.310 --> 00:09:06.210
So if endothermic,
then Q is less than 0,

00:09:06.210 --> 00:09:08.250
and it's all about making
sure that that sum,

00:09:08.250 --> 00:09:10.720
s squared plus t,
is not negative.

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:12.480
What that means is in
order to balance out

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:15.360
the fact that you've
got a negative Q here,

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:20.610
you have to increase T1 in order
to make that sum greater than

00:09:20.610 --> 00:09:21.810
or equal to 0.

00:09:21.810 --> 00:09:22.310
Yes.

00:09:22.310 --> 00:09:23.660
AUDIENCE: So that
condition, s squared

00:09:23.660 --> 00:09:25.300
plus t is greater
than or equal to 0,

00:09:25.300 --> 00:09:28.200
is that basically a condition
for the endothermic reaction

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:28.770
to occur?

00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:30.060
MICHAEL SHORT: That's correct.

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:32.910
If s squared plus t is
smaller than 0, which

00:09:32.910 --> 00:09:36.660
is to say that this whole sum
right here doesn't help you

00:09:36.660 --> 00:09:39.220
balance out the negative
Q, then the reaction

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:40.650
is not going to happen.

00:09:40.650 --> 00:09:42.210
And something else might happen.

00:09:42.210 --> 00:09:46.110
So let's say you were looking at
a case of inelastic scattering

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:49.050
where a neutron would
get absorbed by a nucleus

00:09:49.050 --> 00:09:51.420
and be re-emitted at a
different energy level.

00:09:51.420 --> 00:09:54.300
If the energy is too
small for that to occur,

00:09:54.300 --> 00:09:56.220
then the neutron is not
going to get absorbed.

00:09:56.220 --> 00:09:59.930
Instead it might bounce off
and undergo elastic scattering.

00:09:59.930 --> 00:10:01.410
And as a quick
flash forward, I'll

00:10:01.410 --> 00:10:07.590
show you a quick plot of elastic
and inelastic cross-sections

00:10:07.590 --> 00:10:09.210
that kind of hammers this home.

00:10:09.210 --> 00:10:11.550
You'll be looking at a
lot of these plots, that

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:15.030
are going to be
logarithmic in energy space

00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:20.450
and probably logarithmic in
microscopic cross-section,

00:10:20.450 --> 00:10:23.053
to bring back that
variable from before.

00:10:23.053 --> 00:10:24.470
If you remember,
the cross-section

00:10:24.470 --> 00:10:26.640
is like the probability
that a certain reaction

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:27.860
is going to occur.

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:30.080
The larger the
cross-section, the higher

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:33.650
the reaction rate for a
given flux of particles.

00:10:33.650 --> 00:10:36.300
And let's say we'll split
this into two things.

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:40.610
We'll call it sigma elastic
and sigma inelastic.

00:10:40.610 --> 00:10:42.230
And we'll give them--

00:10:42.230 --> 00:10:44.070
that will be-- oh,
we have colors.

00:10:44.070 --> 00:10:45.200
Let's just use those.

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:46.970
Even better.

00:10:46.970 --> 00:10:48.560
Where's my second color?

00:10:48.560 --> 00:10:49.730
Under the paper.

00:10:49.730 --> 00:10:51.410
Awesome.

00:10:51.410 --> 00:10:53.920
So let's say the elastic
cross-section is in red,

00:10:53.920 --> 00:10:56.540
and the inelastic
cross-section is in green.

00:10:56.540 --> 00:11:03.140
And for white, we'll
plot sigma total.

00:11:03.140 --> 00:11:05.240
Usually, one of these
cross-sections for any old

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:05.842
interaction--

00:11:05.842 --> 00:11:07.550
I'm not even being
specific on which one.

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:10.310
Let's just say neutrons
hitting something big--

00:11:10.310 --> 00:11:12.050
would tend to look like this.

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:15.750
There will be some insanity
here, that we'll discuss,

00:11:15.750 --> 00:11:18.033
and it might start to
increase a little bit

00:11:18.033 --> 00:11:19.200
as it goes to high energies.

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:23.070
And this is definitely
not to scale.

00:11:23.070 --> 00:11:26.340
Just for the purposes
of illustration.

00:11:26.340 --> 00:11:28.830
The elastic cross-section
is going to look something

00:11:28.830 --> 00:11:33.183
like exactly this.

00:11:33.183 --> 00:11:34.850
See how closely I can
draw on top of it.

00:11:39.660 --> 00:11:42.300
So at low energies,
when a neutron

00:11:42.300 --> 00:11:45.270
can't be absorbed and re-emitted
at a different energy,

00:11:45.270 --> 00:11:48.690
the inelastic scattering
process can't happen.

00:11:48.690 --> 00:11:51.220
Which is to say that the
incoming kinetic energy--

00:11:51.220 --> 00:11:54.720
so this log of E right
here, better known

00:11:54.720 --> 00:11:57.360
as T1 in the symbols up there--

00:11:57.360 --> 00:12:00.562
it's not high enough to allow
inelastic scattering to occur.

00:12:00.562 --> 00:12:02.520
So if we want to graph
the inelastic scattering

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:06.290
cross-section, it
will typically look

00:12:06.290 --> 00:12:11.570
like that, where once
you reach your threshold

00:12:11.570 --> 00:12:16.390
energy, determined by
that condition there,

00:12:16.390 --> 00:12:18.790
then the inelastic
scattering turns on

00:12:18.790 --> 00:12:22.460
and it's actually
able to proceed.

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:24.960
So this is why we're getting
into these threshold reactions,

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:26.840
because it helps
you understand why

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:28.970
do some of the
cross-sections that we study

00:12:28.970 --> 00:12:30.980
have the shapes that they do.

00:12:30.980 --> 00:12:33.800
And this holds true
for pretty much

00:12:33.800 --> 00:12:36.140
every inelastic
cross-section I've seen,

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:37.940
is they all--
almost all of them,

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:39.565
if you're starting
at the ground state,

00:12:39.565 --> 00:12:42.050
require some initial
energy input to get going.

00:12:42.050 --> 00:12:44.930
Whereas elastic scattering
can happen at any energy.

00:12:44.930 --> 00:12:47.570
So let's write that last
condition right here.

00:12:50.870 --> 00:12:56.750
Elastic scattering,
which means things just

00:12:56.750 --> 00:13:01.490
bounce off like billiard
balls, you have Q equals 0.

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:05.210
No energy changes
hands, so to speak.

00:13:05.210 --> 00:13:07.190
You just get some
kinetic energy from 1

00:13:07.190 --> 00:13:11.870
being imparted to nucleus 2,
but you don't turn any mass

00:13:11.870 --> 00:13:12.590
into energy.

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:17.330
So any questions here
before we go into--

00:13:17.330 --> 00:13:17.940
yes.

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:19.880
AUDIENCE: If theta isn't
0 for cosine theta,

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:20.922
how would you plug it in?

00:13:20.922 --> 00:13:24.433
If you don't know what the angle
is, that it's not [INAUDIBLE]??

00:13:24.433 --> 00:13:25.850
MICHAEL SHORT: So
the question is,

00:13:25.850 --> 00:13:28.400
if you don't know the angle,
what do you do about it, right?

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:31.140
If you don't-- so in
this case, we've said,

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:33.330
what is the bare minimum
threshold for this reaction

00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:36.860
to occur, and the best way for
that to happen is for theta

00:13:36.860 --> 00:13:38.040
to equal 0.

00:13:38.040 --> 00:13:39.752
If theta is larger,
that will actually

00:13:39.752 --> 00:13:42.210
mean that the reaction is not
allowed to proceed unless you

00:13:42.210 --> 00:13:44.110
get to an even higher energy.

00:13:44.110 --> 00:13:46.290
So this condition still holds.

00:13:46.290 --> 00:13:53.140
But if cosine-- so let's say
if cosine theta is less than 1,

00:13:53.140 --> 00:13:58.410
then the value of s goes down,
and that makes this condition

00:13:58.410 --> 00:14:01.550
harder to satisfy.

00:14:01.550 --> 00:14:03.140
So that's a good question.

00:14:03.140 --> 00:14:06.350
