00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:34.930
a neutron scatters off uranium.

00:20:34.930 --> 00:20:37.160
It's like running at a
truck with a helmet on.

00:20:37.160 --> 00:20:38.940
It will just bounce back.

00:20:38.940 --> 00:20:42.670
So in the case of
theta equals pi--

00:20:42.670 --> 00:20:47.760
so we're going to substitute
in theta equals pi.

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:51.926
Therefore, cosine theta
equals negative 1,

00:20:51.926 --> 00:20:54.880
and we have an even
easier equation.

00:20:54.880 --> 00:21:03.610
0 equals, let's just say,
Tout times 1 plus 1 over A.

00:21:03.610 --> 00:21:05.770
I'm going to arrange
these terms in order

00:21:05.770 --> 00:21:10.120
of their exponent for Tout
since that's our variable again.

00:21:10.120 --> 00:21:15.460
And if this stuff is negative
1, then the 2 minus signs

00:21:15.460 --> 00:21:18.890
cancel conveniently.

00:21:18.890 --> 00:21:25.550
And we have plus
2 root Tin Tout.

00:21:25.550 --> 00:21:26.050
Let's see.

00:21:26.050 --> 00:21:27.270
That's it.

00:21:27.270 --> 00:21:38.530
And we have minus Tin
times 1 over 1 minus A.

00:21:38.530 --> 00:21:40.960
Ideally, we'd like to try
to simplify this as much

00:21:40.960 --> 00:21:42.580
as possible.

00:21:42.580 --> 00:21:44.213
So let's combine.

00:21:44.213 --> 00:21:45.880
Let's try to get
everything in some sort

00:21:45.880 --> 00:21:48.070
of a common denominator,
because that

00:21:48.070 --> 00:21:49.720
would make things a lot easier.

00:21:49.720 --> 00:21:53.830
If we multiply each of
these 1's by A over A--

00:21:53.830 --> 00:22:03.970
so let's put that as a step,
because we can totally do

00:22:03.970 --> 00:22:05.770
that--

00:22:05.770 --> 00:22:12.220
we get 0 over Tout
times A over A plus 1

00:22:12.220 --> 00:22:24.250
over A plus 2 root Tin
Tout minus Tin times A

00:22:24.250 --> 00:22:28.270
over A minus 1 over A.

00:22:28.270 --> 00:22:29.770
At this point, we can--

00:22:29.770 --> 00:22:32.740
well, everything's in
common terms, right?

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:37.480
We can just extend that fraction
sign and put the sign in here.

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:40.930
Extend the fraction sign,
put the sign in here.

00:22:43.882 --> 00:22:49.290
And we'll just say that's
A. We'll say that's A.

00:22:49.290 --> 00:22:52.110
Last step that we'll do
is try and isolate Tout

00:22:52.110 --> 00:22:54.840
so at least one of our quadratic
factors is going to be simple,

00:22:54.840 --> 00:22:56.690
like 1.

00:22:56.690 --> 00:23:04.570
So next step,
divide by A plus 1.

00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:10.810
And then we get 0 equals
just Tout plus 2 over A plus

00:23:10.810 --> 00:23:26.330
one root Tin Tout minus Tin
times A minus 1 over A plus 1.

00:23:26.330 --> 00:23:29.150
Now we've got a simple-looking
quadratic equation,

00:23:29.150 --> 00:23:31.490
even though it's quadratic
in the square root of Tout.

00:23:31.490 --> 00:23:31.990
Yes.

00:23:31.990 --> 00:23:35.368
AUDIENCE: What happened to
the A from the denominator?

00:23:35.368 --> 00:23:36.410
MICHAEL SHORT: Let's see.

00:23:36.410 --> 00:23:37.827
AUDIENCE: Could
it be Tout over A?

00:23:42.062 --> 00:23:43.270
MICHAEL SHORT: What did I do?

00:23:43.270 --> 00:23:45.320
Did I miss an A
or dividing by A?

00:23:45.320 --> 00:23:46.760
AUDIENCE: The last
two equations.

00:23:46.760 --> 00:23:47.870
MICHAEL SHORT: It's
from back here?

00:23:47.870 --> 00:23:48.360
AUDIENCE: No, no, no.

00:23:48.360 --> 00:23:49.880
It's probably the
step you just did.

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:51.260
MICHAEL SHORT: Just these steps.

00:23:51.260 --> 00:23:53.480
AUDIENCE: So you
divide by A plus 1.

00:23:53.480 --> 00:23:54.980
MICHAEL SHORT: Ah, I see.

00:23:54.980 --> 00:23:56.720
AUDIENCE: Should
it be Tout over A?

00:23:56.720 --> 00:23:57.565
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:23:57.565 --> 00:23:58.940
MICHAEL SHORT:
Yes, you're right.

00:23:58.940 --> 00:24:00.470
So I want to make
sure I didn't skip

00:24:00.470 --> 00:24:02.180
a step in dividing
an A. Let me just

00:24:02.180 --> 00:24:04.172
check something real quick.

00:24:04.172 --> 00:24:05.630
AUDIENCE: There
should've been an A

00:24:05.630 --> 00:24:08.977
in the minus 2 square root.

00:24:08.977 --> 00:24:10.310
MICHAEL SHORT: Oh, you're right.

00:24:10.310 --> 00:24:14.300
If we go back to
our Q equation--

00:24:14.300 --> 00:24:16.190
let's see.

00:24:16.190 --> 00:24:19.130
There's an M4
missing, isn't there?

00:24:19.130 --> 00:24:21.296
That's it.

00:24:21.296 --> 00:24:22.220
Hah.

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:26.150
See, this is what happens when
