00:24:48.750 --> 00:24:51.150
OK, cool.

00:24:51.150 --> 00:24:56.360
So at this point, this
is a quadratic in root

00:24:56.360 --> 00:25:03.350
Tout, where we have--

00:25:03.350 --> 00:25:07.590
what are our a, b, and c terms
for this quadratic formula?

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:10.130
So what's a first of all if
it's quadratic in root Tout?

00:25:14.597 --> 00:25:15.550
AUDIENCE: 1?

00:25:15.550 --> 00:25:16.482
MICHAEL SHORT: Just 1.

00:25:16.482 --> 00:25:18.440
That was part of the goal
of this manipulation,

00:25:18.440 --> 00:25:21.440
is to make at least one of
these things pretty simple.

00:25:21.440 --> 00:25:22.010
What's b?

00:25:25.530 --> 00:25:29.048
AUDIENCE: 2 over A plus
1 times radical Tin?

00:25:29.048 --> 00:25:29.840
MICHAEL SHORT: Yes.

00:25:29.840 --> 00:25:32.610
2 root Tin over A plus 1.

00:25:32.610 --> 00:25:34.590
And c is just that
whole term right there.

00:25:40.440 --> 00:25:42.300
I'll do this up here.

00:25:42.300 --> 00:25:46.710
So then we can say root
Tout equals negative

00:25:46.710 --> 00:25:55.360
b plus or minus the
square root of b squared.

00:25:55.360 --> 00:25:58.110
So that's 4 Tin over
A plus 1 squared.

00:26:03.340 --> 00:26:08.140
Minus 4 times a times c,
so just minus 4 times c.

00:26:08.140 --> 00:26:18.820
So minus 4 times negative
Tin A minus 1 over A plus 1.

00:26:18.820 --> 00:26:20.420
So let's see what cancels.

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:24.730
So, first of all, those
minus signs cancel.

00:26:24.730 --> 00:26:27.877
And everything has--
oh, and over 2a.

00:26:27.877 --> 00:26:28.960
Don't want to forget that.

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:32.620
Over 2a, which is just 2.

00:26:32.620 --> 00:26:36.340
First thing we note is that
everything here has a 2 in it,

00:26:36.340 --> 00:26:40.850
either directly as a 2 or
hiding as a square root of 4.

00:26:40.850 --> 00:26:42.930
So we can cancel all of those.

00:26:42.930 --> 00:26:46.736
4, 4, 4, 4.

00:26:46.736 --> 00:26:50.565
Let me make sure that minus
sign is nice and visible.

00:26:50.565 --> 00:26:52.190
What else is common
to everything here?

00:27:00.748 --> 00:27:01.790
Well, I'll tell you what.

00:27:01.790 --> 00:27:04.160
I'll write it all out
simpler without all

00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:06.200
the crossed-out stuff.

00:27:06.200 --> 00:27:12.620
Minus root Tin over A
plus 1 plus or minus

00:27:12.620 --> 00:27:26.380
root Tin over A plus 1 squared
plus Tin times A minus 1

00:27:26.380 --> 00:27:28.330
over A plus 1.

00:27:28.330 --> 00:27:30.220
So with that written
a little simpler,

00:27:30.220 --> 00:27:33.188
what's also common and can be
factored out of everything?

00:27:36.540 --> 00:27:37.870
AUDIENCE: Square root of Ti?

00:27:37.870 --> 00:27:39.037
MICHAEL SHORT: That's right.

00:27:39.037 --> 00:27:40.240
Square root of Tin.

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:43.232
Because there's a root Tin
here, and then you can--

00:27:43.232 --> 00:27:45.190
everything's got a Tin
inside the square roots.

00:27:45.190 --> 00:27:47.590
You can pull that out.

00:27:47.590 --> 00:27:50.770
So we have a direct relation
between root Tout and root Tin.

00:27:54.490 --> 00:27:58.660
Minus 1 over A plus
1 plus or minus

00:27:58.660 --> 00:28:10.180
root 1 over A plus 1 squared
plus A minus 1 over A plus 1.

00:28:10.180 --> 00:28:12.568
What do we do here to
simplify all the junk

00:28:12.568 --> 00:28:13.360
in the square root?

00:28:21.690 --> 00:28:25.273
AUDIENCE: Multiply the right
side by A plus 1 over A plus 1.

00:28:25.273 --> 00:28:26.440
MICHAEL SHORT: That's right.

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:29.700
You can always multiply by
something, better known as 1.

00:28:29.700 --> 00:28:31.660
And that gets
everything here-- just

00:28:31.660 --> 00:28:35.380
like there was a 2 or a root
4 everywhere in the equation,

00:28:35.380 --> 00:28:37.870
or there was a root
Tin and a root Tin

00:28:37.870 --> 00:28:39.490
everywhere else in
the equation, we'll

00:28:39.490 --> 00:28:42.430
do the same thing to get
the A plus 1 out of there.

00:28:42.430 --> 00:28:48.078
So we'll multiply this by
A plus 1 over A plus 1.

00:28:48.078 --> 00:28:49.120
I'll stick it over there.

00:28:53.020 --> 00:28:54.190
OK.

00:28:54.190 --> 00:28:58.660
And we get root Tout equals--

00:28:58.660 --> 00:29:03.400
now everything has an A
plus 1, so let's bring all

00:29:03.400 --> 00:29:05.875
of those outside the fraction.

00:29:11.780 --> 00:29:18.740
Root Tin over A plus
1 times negative 1

00:29:18.740 --> 00:29:27.070
plus or minus the square root
of 1 plus A minus 1, A plus 1.

00:29:27.070 --> 00:29:29.330
Starting to get a lot simpler.

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:32.250
Let's see how much-- if I run
out of space for this one.

00:29:32.250 --> 00:29:36.020
So this stuff right
here is just A squared

00:29:36.020 --> 00:29:40.180
minus A plus A minus 1.

00:29:40.180 --> 00:29:44.390
The minus A and the
plus A cancel out.

00:29:44.390 --> 00:29:47.580
And then the plus 1 and
the minus 1 cancel out.

00:29:47.580 --> 00:29:50.480
And all that's inside the
square root is A squared.

00:29:50.480 --> 00:29:53.600
So the only hopefully
nonlinear board technique,

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:55.470
I'm going to move to the left.

00:29:55.470 --> 00:30:04.010
And we end up with root Tout
equals root Tin over A plus 1.

00:30:04.010 --> 00:30:08.380
And all that's left
there is A minus 1

00:30:08.380 --> 00:30:10.390
if we take the positive root.

00:30:14.450 --> 00:30:16.840
Almost done.

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:18.318
Just square both sides.

00:30:18.318 --> 00:30:20.110
And we should arrive
at a result that might

00:30:20.110 --> 00:30:22.480
look familiar to some of you.

00:30:22.480 --> 00:30:32.790
Tout equals Tin times A minus
1 over A plus 1 squared.

00:30:32.790 --> 00:30:34.850
And we've gotten to
the point now where

00:30:34.850 --> 00:30:38.780
we can determine how much energy
the neutron can possibly lose

00:30:38.780 --> 00:30:40.610
or the recoil
nucleus can possibly

00:30:40.610 --> 00:30:43.680
gain in an elastic collision.

00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:45.650
It's this factor right here.

00:30:45.650 --> 00:30:48.620
I'll use the red since
it's more visible.

00:30:48.620 --> 00:30:54.860
This is usually referred to
in nuclear textbooks as alpha.

00:30:54.860 --> 00:30:58.860
It's sort of the maximum amount
of energy a neutron can lose

00:30:58.860 --> 00:31:01.450
or a recoil nucleus can gain.

00:31:01.450 --> 00:31:07.380
So what we've arrived at is
a pretty important result,

00:31:07.380 --> 00:31:13.730
that, let's say, the energy,
the kinetic energy of a neutron,

00:31:13.730 --> 00:31:20.600
has to be between its initial
kinetic energy and alpha times

00:31:20.600 --> 00:31:22.610
its initial kinetic energy.

00:31:22.610 --> 00:31:24.890
This right here is one
of the ways in which you

00:31:24.890 --> 00:31:27.470
choose a moderator
or a slowing down

00:31:27.470 --> 00:31:30.420
medium for neutrons in reactors.

00:31:30.420 --> 00:31:32.880
So it's this alpha
factor right here

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:35.230
that really distinguishes
what we call a thermal--

00:31:35.230 --> 00:31:36.240
or what is it?

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:38.310
Like a light water reactor
or a thermal spectrum

00:31:38.310 --> 00:31:41.610
reactor from a fast
spectrum reactor.

00:31:41.610 --> 00:31:45.020
Let's look at a couple of
limiting cases to see why.

00:31:45.020 --> 00:31:45.920
Let's see.

00:31:45.920 --> 00:31:47.600
Anyone mind if I
hide this board here?

00:31:47.600 --> 00:31:48.290
Or you have a question?

00:31:48.290 --> 00:31:48.873
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:31:48.873 --> 00:31:53.030
Can you explain why you ended
up dropping the negative case?

00:31:53.030 --> 00:31:54.080
MICHAEL SHORT: Let's see.

00:31:54.080 --> 00:31:58.820
If we took the negative case,
we'd end up with minus 1

00:31:58.820 --> 00:32:05.010
minus A. You just have
an A plus 1 on the top.

00:32:05.010 --> 00:32:05.510
Yes.

00:32:05.510 --> 00:32:07.060
So in that case, you just have--

00:32:07.060 --> 00:32:08.790
let's see.

00:32:08.790 --> 00:32:10.040
You just have root Tin, right?

00:32:12.930 --> 00:32:13.430
Let me see.

00:32:13.430 --> 00:32:15.472
AUDIENCE: Negative
root Tin actually.

00:32:15.472 --> 00:32:16.430
MICHAEL SHORT: Oh, yes.

00:32:16.430 --> 00:32:18.650
So that wouldn't make
very much sense, right?

00:32:18.650 --> 00:32:19.340
Yes.

00:32:19.340 --> 00:32:22.522
So in that case, well, you don't
want to have a negative energy.

00:32:22.522 --> 00:32:24.230
So that case doesn't
make physical sense.

00:32:24.230 --> 00:32:26.210
Thanks for making sure
we explained that.

00:32:26.210 --> 00:32:27.520
And did I see another question?

00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:28.020
Yes.

00:32:28.020 --> 00:32:28.603
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:32:28.603 --> 00:32:30.320
What happened to
the coefficients

00:32:30.320 --> 00:32:31.400
you had before Tin?

00:32:31.400 --> 00:32:33.125
You had 4.

00:32:33.125 --> 00:32:34.900
You needed 4 or 2,
but [INAUDIBLE]..

00:32:34.900 --> 00:32:35.650
MICHAEL SHORT: Ah.

00:32:35.650 --> 00:32:36.150
OK.

00:32:36.150 --> 00:32:39.500
So what I did is I took the
square root of 4 out of every

00:32:39.500 --> 00:32:42.950
term inside the square root
and said, OK, they're all 2's.

00:32:42.950 --> 00:32:44.930
Just like in the next
step, I said, all right,

00:32:44.930 --> 00:32:47.600
there's all of these
A plus 1's, including

00:32:47.600 --> 00:32:50.360
all of these A plus 1's
squares inside the square root,

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:51.530
and took that out.

00:32:51.530 --> 00:32:52.760
Or I think even over here.

00:32:52.760 --> 00:32:55.610
Yes, so the whole thing here
has been combine and destroy.

00:32:58.197 --> 00:33:00.780
Any other questions on what we
did here before I go on to some

00:33:00.780 --> 00:33:02.238
of the implications
of what we got?

00:33:04.600 --> 00:33:05.432
Cool.

00:33:05.432 --> 00:33:07.015
Let's look at a
couple limiting cases.

00:33:09.640 --> 00:33:13.390
I'll rewrite that inequality
right there because that's

00:33:13.390 --> 00:33:14.640
the important one of the day.

00:33:20.760 --> 00:33:23.220
So what is alpha for
typical materials?

00:33:23.220 --> 00:33:28.940
Let's say for hydrogen.
Alpha equals--

00:33:28.940 --> 00:33:34.160
well, it's always A minus
1 over A plus 1 squared.

00:33:34.160 --> 00:33:37.990
And for hydrogen, A
equals equals 1, equals 1.

00:33:37.990 --> 00:33:40.730
And then we have 1 minus
1 in the numerator.

00:33:40.730 --> 00:33:42.860
Alpha equals 0.

00:33:42.860 --> 00:33:45.620
What this means is that
for the case of hydrogen,

00:33:45.620 --> 00:33:51.694
you can lose all of the neutron
energy in a single collision.

00:33:56.140 --> 00:33:59.260
That doesn't mean that you lose
all energy in every collision

00:33:59.260 --> 00:34:01.215
with a hydrogen atom
if you're a neutron,

00:34:01.215 --> 00:34:02.590
but it means that
you can lose up

00:34:02.590 --> 00:34:05.710
to all of your energy
in one single collision.

00:34:05.710 --> 00:34:08.800
And this is what makes
hydrogen such a good moderator

00:34:08.800 --> 00:34:11.770
or a slower down of neutrons,
is when it undergoes

00:34:11.770 --> 00:34:15.820
elastic scattering, especially
at energies below an MeV or so,

00:34:15.820 --> 00:34:18.790
which is where most of the
neutrons in the reactor are,

00:34:18.790 --> 00:34:20.050
it just bounces around.

00:34:20.050 --> 00:34:22.030
And the more it hits
hydrogens, the more

00:34:22.030 --> 00:34:25.222
it imparts energy to those
hydrogens and slows down.

00:34:25.222 --> 00:34:26.889
Why do we want to
slow the neutrons down

00:34:26.889 --> 00:34:28.460
in the first place?

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:31.219
Well, that has to do with
another cross-section,

00:34:31.219 --> 00:34:33.219
that I'm going to draw
if I can find some chalk.

00:34:36.531 --> 00:34:37.989
Like I think I've
mentioned before,

00:34:37.989 --> 00:34:42.080
every nuclear reaction
has its own cross-section.

00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:46.219
And this time I'm going to
introduce a new one called

00:34:46.219 --> 00:34:50.840
sigma fission, the probability,
if a nucleus absorbs

00:34:50.840 --> 00:34:53.179
a neutron, that it undergoes
fission and creates

00:34:53.179 --> 00:34:57.540
more neutrons and like
200 MeV of recoil energy.

00:34:57.540 --> 00:35:01.760
So in this case, I'll
draw it for U235,

00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:04.250
since this is the one I pretty
much remember from memory.

00:35:04.250 --> 00:35:08.240
And it looks
something like that.

00:35:08.240 --> 00:35:12.650
So what you want is for the
neutrons to be at low energies.

00:35:12.650 --> 00:35:17.240
So this would be around the
thermal energy, better known

00:35:17.240 --> 00:35:20.180
as about 0.025 eV.

00:35:20.180 --> 00:35:22.490
Your goal is that the
more neutrons that you

00:35:22.490 --> 00:35:25.020
have in this energy region--

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:27.890
oh, that chalk
erases other chalk.

00:35:27.890 --> 00:35:31.010
The more neutrons you have in
that energy region, the higher

00:35:31.010 --> 00:35:32.720
probability you have a fission.

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:35.270
So this is the basis
behind thermal reactors,

00:35:35.270 --> 00:35:39.200
is the neutrons all start here.

00:35:39.200 --> 00:35:44.740
They're born at
around 1 to 10 MeV.

00:35:44.740 --> 00:35:48.100
They don't undergo fission
very well at 1 to 10 MeV.

00:35:48.100 --> 00:35:50.590
So your goal as a
thermal reactor designer

00:35:50.590 --> 00:35:53.840
is to slow them down as
efficiently as possible.

00:35:53.840 --> 00:35:57.130
What's the most efficient
way to slow down neutrons?

00:35:57.130 --> 00:35:59.680
Cram the reactor
full of hydrogen.

00:35:59.680 --> 00:36:03.810
What's the cheapest and most
hydrogenous substance we know?

00:36:03.810 --> 00:36:05.250
Water.

00:36:05.250 --> 00:36:10.000
This is why water makes such
a good reactor moderator.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:11.020
It's pretty cool.

00:36:11.020 --> 00:36:13.770
There's also lots of other
reasons that we use water.

00:36:13.770 --> 00:36:16.650
It's everywhere, which is
another way of saying cheap.

00:36:16.650 --> 00:36:18.330
It's pretty chemically inert.

00:36:18.330 --> 00:36:20.070
There are corrosion
problems in reactors,

00:36:20.070 --> 00:36:22.710
but it doesn't just
spontaneously combust

00:36:22.710 --> 00:36:26.880
when you see air, like sodium
does, another reactor coolant.

00:36:26.880 --> 00:36:29.490
It takes a lot of
energy to heat it up.

00:36:29.490 --> 00:36:34.242
So it's specific heat
capacity, the CP of water,

00:36:34.242 --> 00:36:34.950
if you remember--

00:36:34.950 --> 00:36:42.210
I think it's-- was it
4.184 joules per gram?

00:36:42.210 --> 00:36:44.645
That's a point.

00:36:44.645 --> 00:36:47.100
One of the highest
substances that we know of.

00:36:47.100 --> 00:36:49.800
So you can put a lot
of that recoil energy

00:36:49.800 --> 00:36:52.350
or a lot of heat
energy into this water

00:36:52.350 --> 00:36:54.000
without raising its
temperature as much

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:55.740
as a comparative substance.

00:36:55.740 --> 00:36:59.137
Metals can have heat capacity's
like three or four times lower.

00:36:59.137 --> 00:37:01.470
So you wouldn't necessarily
want to use a metal coolant.

00:37:01.470 --> 00:37:03.180
Or would you?

00:37:03.180 --> 00:37:05.700
In what cases would you
want to use a metal coolant

00:37:05.700 --> 00:37:06.630
for a reactor?

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:10.140
Has anyone ever heard of
liquid metal reactors before?

00:37:10.140 --> 00:37:10.900
Just a couple.

00:37:10.900 --> 00:37:11.400
Good.

00:37:11.400 --> 00:37:13.350
I get to be the first
one to tell you.

00:37:13.350 --> 00:37:16.980
I did my whole PhD on alloys
for the liquid lead reactor.

00:37:16.980 --> 00:37:23.230
So let's take a look at lead,
which has an A of about--

00:37:23.230 --> 00:37:26.050
let's call it 200.

00:37:26.050 --> 00:37:28.390
I think there's some
isotopes, like 203 or so.

00:37:28.390 --> 00:37:31.390
There's probably an
isotope called lead 200.

00:37:31.390 --> 00:37:33.790
What would alpha be for lead?

00:37:37.380 --> 00:37:39.220
Well, let's just
plug in the numbers.

00:37:39.220 --> 00:37:41.842
A minus 1 is 199.

00:37:41.842 --> 00:37:44.740
A plus 1 is 201.

00:37:44.740 --> 00:37:45.520
Square that.

00:37:48.250 --> 00:37:51.080
Almost 1.

00:37:51.080 --> 00:37:51.580
Almost.

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:57.910
This means that when neutrons
hit something like lead,

00:37:57.910 --> 00:38:00.040
basically don't slow down.

00:38:00.040 --> 00:38:04.240
They can lose at least
none and at most almost

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:06.032
none of their energy.

00:38:06.032 --> 00:38:07.490
And this is the
basis behind what's

00:38:07.490 --> 00:38:10.820
called fast reactors if you
want to use a coolant that

00:38:10.820 --> 00:38:13.190
keeps the neutrons very fast.

00:38:13.190 --> 00:38:15.918
Because for uranium 238,
there's what's called a--

00:38:15.918 --> 00:38:17.960
well, what you do is you
want to capture neutrons

00:38:17.960 --> 00:38:22.670
with uranium 238, make plutonium
239, and then breed that.

00:38:22.670 --> 00:38:29.493
Or uranium 238 has got its
fast fission cross-section.

00:38:29.493 --> 00:38:31.910
I don't think I want to get
into bringing it on the screen

00:38:31.910 --> 00:38:34.590
today since we're
almost five of five of.

00:38:34.590 --> 00:38:36.590
What I will say is there's
lots of other reactor

00:38:36.590 --> 00:38:37.950
coolants besides water.

00:38:37.950 --> 00:38:39.950
And it sounds to me like
almost no one had heard

00:38:39.950 --> 00:38:41.450
of a liquid metal reactor.

00:38:41.450 --> 00:38:43.370
Why would you want
to use a liquid metal

00:38:43.370 --> 00:38:48.760
as a coolant besides keeping
the neutrons at high energy?

00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:49.690
Anyone have any ideas?

00:38:53.500 --> 00:38:57.050
What sort of properties do
you want out of a coolant?

00:38:57.050 --> 00:38:59.790
Not even for a reactor
but for anything.

00:38:59.790 --> 00:39:00.790
AUDIENCE: Heat transfer.

00:39:00.790 --> 00:39:02.470
MICHAEL SHORT:
Good heat transfer.

00:39:02.470 --> 00:39:05.110
Metals are extremely
thermally conductive.

00:39:05.110 --> 00:39:07.750
So if you want to get the
heat out of the fuel rods

00:39:07.750 --> 00:39:09.850
and into the coolant and
then out to make steam

00:39:09.850 --> 00:39:12.790
for a turbine, liquid metals
are a pretty awesome coolant

00:39:12.790 --> 00:39:16.540
to use because they conduct
heat extremely well.

00:39:16.540 --> 00:39:17.080
What else?

00:39:19.630 --> 00:39:20.740
Let's try and think now.

00:39:20.740 --> 00:39:22.360
If you were a reactor
designer, you don't just

00:39:22.360 --> 00:39:24.130
have to make the reactor
work but you want

00:39:24.130 --> 00:39:26.450
to make it avoid accidents.

00:39:26.450 --> 00:39:29.710
What sort of thermodynamic
properties about metals

00:39:29.710 --> 00:39:31.738
could prevent accidents
from happening?

00:39:31.738 --> 00:39:32.828
AUDIENCE: They solidify.

00:39:32.828 --> 00:39:33.620
MICHAEL SHORT: Yes.

00:39:33.620 --> 00:39:34.740
So there's one problem.

00:39:34.740 --> 00:39:36.170
They could solidify.

00:39:36.170 --> 00:39:38.810
So coolants that have
been chosen for reactors

00:39:38.810 --> 00:39:41.660
have been things like
sodium, which melts just

00:39:41.660 --> 00:39:44.840
below 100 Celsius, liquid
lead-bismuth, which

00:39:44.840 --> 00:39:46.550
melts at 123 Celsius.

00:39:46.550 --> 00:39:49.180
And I know because I've
it in a frying pan before.

00:39:49.180 --> 00:39:51.590
So I did four years of research
on liquid lead-bismuth,

00:39:51.590 --> 00:39:54.110
and if there's anyone that's
gotten enough exposure to that,

00:39:54.110 --> 00:39:54.800
it's me.

00:39:54.800 --> 00:39:56.750
It does not seem to
have affected my brain

00:39:56.750 --> 00:39:59.780
too much because I only
made like two major mistakes

00:39:59.780 --> 00:40:01.580
on today's board.

00:40:01.580 --> 00:40:03.480
Good enough.

00:40:03.480 --> 00:40:03.980
Yes.

00:40:03.980 --> 00:40:07.370
So we've got hundreds of pounds
of lead-bismuth sitting around.

00:40:07.370 --> 00:40:08.990
It's pretty inert stuff.

00:40:08.990 --> 00:40:13.500
It's really dense, so it
can store a lot of heat.

00:40:13.500 --> 00:40:16.030
The other thing is
the boiling point.

00:40:16.030 --> 00:40:18.280
Anyone know what
temperature metals boil at?

00:40:21.022 --> 00:40:22.850
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:40:22.850 --> 00:40:25.130
MICHAEL SHORT:
Extremely high, yes.

00:40:25.130 --> 00:40:31.250
Sodium boils at approximately
exactly 893 degrees Celsius.

00:40:31.250 --> 00:40:36.080
Liquid lead-bismuth boils at
approximately exactly 1,670

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:37.130
Celsius.

00:40:37.130 --> 00:40:39.110
You'll actually melt the
steel that the reactor

00:40:39.110 --> 00:40:41.780
is made of before you
boil off your coolant.

00:40:41.780 --> 00:40:43.370
And if you boil
your coolant, you

00:40:43.370 --> 00:40:44.870
have no way of
cooling the reactor,

00:40:44.870 --> 00:40:46.760
and that's something
you want to avoid.

00:40:46.760 --> 00:40:51.510
Water boils at
approximately 325--

00:40:51.510 --> 00:40:56.750
let's say 288 to 340 Celsius
depending on the pressure

00:40:56.750 --> 00:40:58.310
that's used in the reactors.

00:40:58.310 --> 00:41:00.470
And that does get reached
sometimes, especially

00:41:00.470 --> 00:41:01.940
in accident conditions.

00:41:01.940 --> 00:41:05.450
So if you want to make something
relatively Fukushima-proof,

00:41:05.450 --> 00:41:07.490
then you don't want
the coolant to boil.

00:41:07.490 --> 00:41:11.950
So use a liquid metal, which
introduces other problems.

00:41:11.950 --> 00:41:14.040
It also introduces
some other problems.

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:17.190
I'm going to flash forward a bit
to neutrons and reactor design.

00:41:17.190 --> 00:41:20.757
Because it does take time for
this scattering to happen.

00:41:20.757 --> 00:41:22.590
These collisions, they
happen pretty quickly

00:41:22.590 --> 00:41:25.270
but they do take a
finite amount of time.

00:41:25.270 --> 00:41:26.820
And in the meantime,
you can have

00:41:26.820 --> 00:41:29.100
what's called
feedback coefficients,

00:41:29.100 --> 00:41:32.130
natural bits of physics that
help your reactor stay stable

00:41:32.130 --> 00:41:35.040
or they don't, depending
on whether it's called

00:41:35.040 --> 00:41:37.950
negative or positive feedback.

00:41:37.950 --> 00:41:42.540
So we can have either
negative or positive feedback.

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:49.750
I'll give you one simple
example that I'll just

00:41:49.750 --> 00:41:52.180
introduce conceptually,
and we'll actually

00:41:52.180 --> 00:41:53.890
explain it a little
mathematically later

00:41:53.890 --> 00:41:55.010
in the course.

00:41:55.010 --> 00:41:57.400
Let's talk about
coolant density.

00:41:57.400 --> 00:41:59.650
If you were to heat
up your reactor

00:41:59.650 --> 00:42:02.923
and the coolant were
to get less dense,

00:42:02.923 --> 00:42:04.840
what do you think would
happen to the reaction

00:42:04.840 --> 00:42:09.040
rate of, well, anything--
scattering, fission,

00:42:09.040 --> 00:42:10.408
absorption?

00:42:10.408 --> 00:42:11.650
AUDIENCE: Go down.

00:42:11.650 --> 00:42:12.430
MICHAEL SHORT: It
should go down.

00:42:12.430 --> 00:42:13.472
Why do you think that is?

00:42:13.472 --> 00:42:15.852
AUDIENCE: Because there's
not as many particles that's

00:42:15.852 --> 00:42:17.732
close together, so [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:17.732 --> 00:42:18.690
MICHAEL SHORT: Exactly.

00:42:18.690 --> 00:42:19.570
Yes.

00:42:19.570 --> 00:42:22.120
To reintroduce a bit of the
cross-section stuff I mentioned

00:42:22.120 --> 00:42:25.270
last time, the
microscopic cross-section

00:42:25.270 --> 00:42:27.760
is the probability that,
let's say, one nucleus

00:42:27.760 --> 00:42:30.140
hits one other nucleus.

00:42:30.140 --> 00:42:32.920
If you then multiply
by the number density

00:42:32.920 --> 00:42:35.290
or how many of
them are there, you

00:42:35.290 --> 00:42:38.260
end up with the
macroscopic cross-section.

00:42:38.260 --> 00:42:43.330
So I'll label this as
micro, label this as macro.

00:42:43.330 --> 00:42:46.560
And then the macroscopic
cross-section

00:42:46.560 --> 00:42:52.930
times your neutron flux
gives you your reaction rate.

00:42:52.930 --> 00:42:56.110
So if you want to get less
moderating happening, or less

00:42:56.110 --> 00:42:58.570
fission, or less
absorption, the simplest way

00:42:58.570 --> 00:43:01.270
is-- well, that's a
property of the material.

00:43:01.270 --> 00:43:03.310
That's whatever your
reactor is doing.

00:43:03.310 --> 00:43:04.960
You can decrease
the number density

00:43:04.960 --> 00:43:08.630
by heating things up and
decreasing the density.

00:43:08.630 --> 00:43:11.600
So this is one of those cases
where you can use the reactor

00:43:11.600 --> 00:43:14.780
to quickly respond with physics
before you could respond

00:43:14.780 --> 00:43:16.280
with human intervention.

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:18.590
If you want, let's
say, a extra power

00:43:18.590 --> 00:43:21.380
transient or a sudden
increase in heat

00:43:21.380 --> 00:43:24.200
to slow down the nuclear
reaction and not speed it up,

00:43:24.200 --> 00:43:27.870
you'd pick a moderator
that behaves in this way.

00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:30.410
So in this case, water
would get less dense,

00:43:30.410 --> 00:43:34.400
it would moderate less
well, and put fewer neutrons

00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:37.600
in the high-probability
fission region.

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:39.130
Then let's think
about what happens

00:43:39.130 --> 00:43:42.460
if you're depending on
your neutrons to stay fast

00:43:42.460 --> 00:43:43.840
or at high energy.

00:43:43.840 --> 00:43:46.240
Let's say you were to
have a really bad day

00:43:46.240 --> 00:43:48.840
and boil your liquid sodium.

00:43:48.840 --> 00:43:51.150
All of a sudden, what
little moderating power

00:43:51.150 --> 00:43:55.350
exists in that sodium
disappears or gets even lower,

00:43:55.350 --> 00:43:58.380
and that would cause your
reactor power to increase.

00:43:58.380 --> 00:44:01.530
So one of the dangers of
fast spectrum reactors

00:44:01.530 --> 00:44:04.740
is positive-- what's called
positive void coefficient.

00:44:04.740 --> 00:44:08.310
Or if you make a bubble
of gaseous sodium,

00:44:08.310 --> 00:44:10.830
your power increases
rather than decreases.

00:44:10.830 --> 00:44:12.120
That would increase the heat.

00:44:12.120 --> 00:44:13.620
That would cause
the power to go up.

00:44:13.620 --> 00:44:14.828
That would increase the heat.

00:44:14.828 --> 00:44:16.410
That would cause
the power to go up.

00:44:16.410 --> 00:44:18.660
Luckily, there are many,
many other negative feedback

00:44:18.660 --> 00:44:20.610
mechanisms that
could be built in

00:44:20.610 --> 00:44:23.700
to make sure the overall
feedback coefficients are still

00:44:23.700 --> 00:44:26.540
negative.

00:44:26.540 --> 00:44:29.240
